name: 3-fluoro-4-methoxyphenylacetonitrile
Reason: The melting point of a compound can be shifted by various functional groups within its structure. The basic unit we will consider is phenylacetonitrile, which has a melting point around 71°C. Each functional group in 3-fluoro-4-methoxyphenylacetonitrile will impact this base melting point. The fluorine atom, being an electron-withdrawing group through its inductive effect, typically increases melting point due to enhanced molecular stability and intermolecular interactions (+5°C). The methoxy group is a larger and electron-donating group; electron-donating groups typically decrease the melting point as they destabilize the structure and reduce intermolecular interactions, but the oxygen can also form hydrogen bonds which might counteract this effect (-10°C). The additional alkyl cyanide (acetonitrile group) is a strong electron-withdrawing group, which increases melting point significantly due to dipole-dipole interactions and potential for linear dimerization with other molecules (+15°C). Combining these changes yields the predicted melting point.
